<font color="#FF0000">I NEED A MOMENT.</font><br>
<tt>Mon Feb 17 22:31:08 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
To all of you, I misread this site on my first vist.<br>
Maybe everyone was just on some mission I wasn't tuning<br>
into that night. Forgive my ignorance. Nothing like a<br>
FNG to miss the meaning of the music.<br><br>
I would like to impart something to all. There was a point<br>
where I thought I was getting over the Nam, starting to<br>
distance myself from the absolute turmoil I had each and<br>
every day for about a decade during the 70's. I have to<br>
keep learning over and over again that it hasn't gone away.<br>
I have just gotten used to it. Kind of like a wound that<br>
won't go away. You just go on with life and take your<br>
medicine and ignore the pain. My wife reminded me of that<br>
the other night. We were discussing how my episodes were<br>
further apart. But she said, &quot;I see it in your eyes. You<br>
still function now, but that far away look and shortness<br>
is there. I know it's there and don't do that. Be just like<br>
we were early on, when you found some peace in my caring.&quot;<br><br>
That hit home. Getting old is a bitch. I'm getting to be an<br>
old fucking grey beard. Sometimes I think the damn Nam is<br>
keeping my head in my youth. Because it stays so close,<br>
I am always there, at that haunting time. Hell, maybe it's<br>
not a curse but in a way a blessing. It keeps my mind young.<br><br>
I know I'm rambling. Today I was at a stop light. I got a<br>
little sticker on the bumper of my car, you know, &quot;I'm a<br>
Vietnam Vet and proud of it&quot;. I was at a train crossing and<br>
waiting it out. A guy got out of his car behind me. I was<br>
watching him in the rear view. Can't be too careful.<br><br>
He knocked on my window and when I rolled it down, he stuck<br>
out his hand. Said &quot;You a Nam Vet?&quot; I said yeah. He said<br>
&quot;Thank you Sir. I never said that in the 70's to no one.<br>
I feel bad about it. You guys are real Americans, and I<br>
never thanked anyone. Well, I thank You.&quot;<br><br>
It didn't hit me at first. That don't happen often. Then<br>
I cried. Jesus, it felt good to cry. I thank that guy<br>
tonight. Wherever he is, Thank You.<br><br>
 
<p><code>-- carnival@ont.com  (JJ the Boonirat) </code><p>


